i), writers (Kim Fu, Kai Cheng Thom, Monique Truong), and video, multimedia, and conceptual artists (Laurel Nakadate, Yoko Ono, Mika Tajima), Huang challenges neoliberal narratives of assimilation that erase Asianness. By using sound, touch, and affect, these artists and writers create new frameworks for affirming Asianness as a source of political and social critique and innovative forms of life and creativity.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexAsian American authorsxThemes, motives. 0aAsian American artxThemes, motives. 0aAsian American arty20th century. 0aAsian American arty21st century. 0aAsian American artists. 0aGroup identity in art. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023623?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023623/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles